WEBVTT

00:01.335 --> 00:02.628
WOMAN:
Previously on
When Calls the Heart...

00:02.628 --> 00:04.880
CURTIS:
As soon as you fire,
we'll take the wagon.

00:04.880 --> 00:06.465
FLOYD:
You sure you want them dead?

00:06.465 --> 00:08.550
GLENN: Is that a problem?
FLOYD: Not for me.

00:08.550 --> 00:11.345
I can't afford to take time off.
Phillip only gets one childhood,

00:11.345 --> 00:13.681
and you don't get to do it over.
How are you getting on

00:13.681 --> 00:16.183
with Madame Mayor?
Perhaps it'd be easier dealing

00:16.183 --> 00:18.602
with a more reasonable man.
Perhaps.

00:18.602 --> 00:20.061
[♪♪♪]

00:23.273 --> 00:25.818
Has anyone applied
to be the new cook yet?

00:25.818 --> 00:27.945
No, not yet, but
I hope it happens soon.

00:27.945 --> 00:29.363
We are busier than ever.

00:29.363 --> 00:31.365
I know exactly what you mean.
Just when I thought

00:31.365 --> 00:33.325
I had enough supplies
for all of our students,

00:33.325 --> 00:34.994
suddenly, a new bunch
of kids shows up.

00:34.994 --> 00:37.454
We'll figure something out.

00:37.454 --> 00:40.499
I heard you made a deal
with the railroad.

00:41.583 --> 00:43.293
I did what I thought was right.

00:43.293 --> 00:46.254
Abigail, I don't like
to second guess people, but...

00:46.254 --> 00:48.799
But that's exactly
what you're going to do.

00:48.799 --> 00:50.718
I just don't see
how letting the railroad pay

00:50.718 --> 00:53.178
less than their fair share of
taxes is good for Hope Valley--

00:53.178 --> 00:54.680
Elizabeth,
with all due respect,

00:54.680 --> 00:56.682
you don't have to understand.
That is my job.

00:56.682 --> 00:58.017
Sorry.

00:59.267 --> 01:00.644
No, I'm sorry.

01:00.644 --> 01:02.521
The budget
is not the only thing

01:02.521 --> 01:03.981
stretched to its breaking point.

01:03.981 --> 01:06.191
I know you're under
a lot of pressure.

01:07.818 --> 01:09.904
Jack promised
to walk me to school.

01:09.904 --> 01:11.405
Can we talk about this
another time?

01:11.405 --> 01:13.991
Maybe when someone else
is mayor.

01:13.991 --> 01:15.325
[BOTH CHUCKLING]

01:17.786 --> 01:19.246
Whoa, slow down
there, young man.

01:19.246 --> 01:20.956
Did you brush your teeth?
Yes, ma'am.

01:20.956 --> 01:22.958
Hmm, you didn't just
get the toothbrush wet

01:22.958 --> 01:24.292
like last time, did you?

01:25.586 --> 01:27.379
Ah, good.

01:27.379 --> 01:30.007
Do you think Pastor Frank would
like to play dominoes tonight?

01:30.007 --> 01:33.635
It'll be just us for dinner.

01:33.635 --> 01:36.095
But we have spaghetti night
with Pastor Frank every week.

01:36.095 --> 01:37.598
I know we do.

01:37.598 --> 01:40.141
Are you mad at each other?

01:40.141 --> 01:42.644
Cody, it's hard to explain.

01:42.644 --> 01:45.731
But we are going to have
a great time tonight, I promise.

01:45.731 --> 01:47.983
I have a special dessert
planned.

01:49.651 --> 01:51.779
Okay, off to school,
you don't want to be late.

01:59.703 --> 02:01.204
I think, if you don't mind,

02:01.204 --> 02:03.415
I'd like to move dinner
till a little later tonight.

02:03.415 --> 02:04.708
Anything
I can help with?

02:04.708 --> 02:06.710
Only if you like
grading math tests.

02:06.710 --> 02:09.337
Hmm, I think
I'll leave that to you.

02:09.337 --> 02:10.631
So how's 7:00?

02:10.631 --> 02:12.049
I'm making a pot roast.

02:12.049 --> 02:13.926
Sounds adventurous.

02:13.926 --> 02:15.427
I've made
pot roast before.

02:15.427 --> 02:16.678
Once.

02:16.678 --> 02:18.430
And it was
unbelievable.

02:18.430 --> 02:20.057
Constable Jack Thornton?

02:22.810 --> 02:24.103
[GASPS]

02:24.103 --> 02:26.939
Didn't I teach you
better than that?

02:26.939 --> 02:28.398
[♪♪♪]

02:31.068 --> 02:32.402
[GRUNTS]

02:35.781 --> 02:37.908
[♪♪♪]

02:56.551 --> 02:59.847
Uh, would someone here
like to explain?

02:59.847 --> 03:02.057
Elizabeth Thatcher,
I want you to meet

03:02.057 --> 03:04.059
Constable Douglas Burke.

03:04.059 --> 03:06.020
Doug.
And it's Corporal.

03:06.020 --> 03:07.855
I didn't know.
Congratulations.

03:07.855 --> 03:09.188
All thanks to you.

03:09.188 --> 03:10.774
I don't understand.

03:10.774 --> 03:13.861
Get in line. Why did you
just try to hit him?

03:13.861 --> 03:15.696
It was long overdue.

03:15.696 --> 03:17.196
Doug was one
of the junior cadets

03:17.196 --> 03:18.699
I mentored at the academy.

03:18.699 --> 03:20.993
We used to play practical
jokes on each other.

03:20.993 --> 03:23.162
That's only partly right.
Jack outranked me,

03:23.162 --> 03:24.705
so he got to play the jokes.

03:24.705 --> 03:26.957
I had to suffer them,
in silence.

03:26.957 --> 03:28.291
[CHUCKLES]

03:28.291 --> 03:29.710
So, what prank
was that for?

03:29.710 --> 03:31.003
Choose one.

03:32.462 --> 03:34.422
Regimental Review Day.

03:34.422 --> 03:36.175
A quart of goat milk
in your boots.

03:36.175 --> 03:38.802
Took me two weeks to get
rid of that smell.

03:38.802 --> 03:40.637
Boys will be boys.
[LAUGHING] Yeah.

03:40.637 --> 03:41.930
Well...

03:41.930 --> 03:43.306
Don't let me
stand in the way.

03:43.306 --> 03:44.683
It was nice
to meet you.

03:44.683 --> 03:45.976
Miss.

03:49.604 --> 03:51.398
How'd you get so lucky?

03:51.398 --> 03:53.192
I honestly have no idea.

03:53.192 --> 03:55.027
So, what are you
doing here anyway?

03:55.027 --> 03:56.570
Superintendent Collins
offered me

03:56.570 --> 03:58.446
the position
that you turned down.

03:58.446 --> 03:59.740
He did?

03:59.740 --> 04:01.075
I'm leading
a squad of Mounties

04:01.075 --> 04:03.077
up to the Northern
Territories.

04:08.832 --> 04:10.209
Well, I'm proud of you, Doug.

04:10.209 --> 04:12.002
Thanks, Jack.

04:12.002 --> 04:13.795
We're bunking at the saloon
for the night.

04:13.795 --> 04:15.797
I was hoping you'd have
some time to catch up.

04:15.797 --> 04:17.298
Of course.

04:17.298 --> 04:19.509
Come on, let me buy you
a cup of coffee.

04:21.511 --> 04:23.138
[SCHOOL BELL RINGING]

04:23.138 --> 04:25.390
Good morning, everyone! Good
morning, good morning.

04:25.390 --> 04:26.934
Good morning.
Come on in, Robert.

04:26.934 --> 04:28.185
Good morning.

04:28.185 --> 04:29.895
Good morning, Philip.

04:29.895 --> 04:32.397
Why don't you take your seat?
We're about to get started.

04:32.397 --> 04:34.149
I'm so glad you made it
to the carnival.

04:34.149 --> 04:36.818
I know it was
important to him.

04:36.818 --> 04:38.737
He's still struggling
a little to keep up.

04:38.737 --> 04:39.988
Maybe you could read to him.

04:39.988 --> 04:41.615
It helps,

04:41.615 --> 04:43.992
and it'll give you a chance
to spend some time with him.

04:43.992 --> 04:45.786
I'm doing the best I can,
Miss Thatcher.

04:50.874 --> 04:52.417
[SIGHS]

04:52.417 --> 04:54.795
All right, everyone,
let's get settled.

04:57.798 --> 05:01.635
Now, we have a very fun project
that we'll be starting today.

05:01.635 --> 05:02.970
Can Brownie
be part of it?

05:02.970 --> 05:04.429
Of course.

05:04.429 --> 05:06.347
Everyone in your family
will be a part of it.

05:06.347 --> 05:08.183
This week, you're each
going to be making

05:08.183 --> 05:09.434
a family tree.

05:09.434 --> 05:11.478
What's that?
It's an exercise

05:11.478 --> 05:13.605
where you trace
the history of your relatives

05:13.605 --> 05:15.440
back as far as you can go,

05:15.440 --> 05:17.734
and then you share
that information with the class.

05:17.734 --> 05:19.569
My grandpa played piano
at Carnegie Hall.

05:19.569 --> 05:22.281
Oh. Well, make sure you write
that down, Timmy.

05:22.281 --> 05:24.825
Now, everyone, let's take out
our pencils and our papers,

05:24.825 --> 05:26.994
and let's get started.

05:26.994 --> 05:28.328
Any word on the men

05:28.328 --> 05:29.955
who tried to rob
the payroll coach?

05:29.955 --> 05:33.125
Don't worry, the Mounties will
catch them soon enough.

05:33.125 --> 05:34.793
MAN:
Let me ask you something,

05:34.793 --> 05:37.171
how is it someone that beautiful
isn't already spoken for?

05:37.171 --> 05:40.507
I don't know much about her,
except that she's a good nurse.

05:40.507 --> 05:42.801
I bet there's
a lot to learn.

05:42.801 --> 05:45.470
Did you hear back from
Mr. Jenkins from the bank?

05:45.470 --> 05:47.472
He said we can count
payroll tomorrow night,

05:47.472 --> 05:49.016
after he closes up.

05:49.016 --> 05:50.309
I'll be there.

05:50.309 --> 05:52.727
[♪♪♪]

06:00.777 --> 06:02.361
Good morning, Henry.

06:02.361 --> 06:05.199
Good morning. The townsfolk
seem quite pleased with you.

06:05.199 --> 06:06.533
That was a bold move,

06:06.533 --> 06:08.202
standing up to the railroad
like that.

06:08.202 --> 06:10.287
Some people don't think
I stood up enough.

06:10.287 --> 06:12.789
But I've heard it said
that the best compromise

06:12.789 --> 06:15.125
is one where both sides
are a little unhappy.

06:15.125 --> 06:17.711
In this case, I think
I'd have to disagree with that.

06:17.711 --> 06:19.587
I did my homework, Henry.

06:19.587 --> 06:21.422
Other mayors have worked
with the railroad

06:21.422 --> 06:23.008
and not given away the store.

06:23.008 --> 06:25.802
Well, I think they'll
pay for it sooner or later.

06:25.802 --> 06:27.637
Well, that's your opinion.

06:30.307 --> 06:31.766
[♪♪♪]

06:53.454 --> 06:54.748
[CLEARS THROAT]

06:54.748 --> 06:56.875
Oh! Mrs. Coulter,
I didn't see you there.

06:56.875 --> 06:58.168
Hmm.

06:58.168 --> 07:00.128
I-I was just
looking at...

07:00.128 --> 07:02.339
pickles.

07:02.339 --> 07:04.423
Oh, Murphy, pickles indeed.

07:04.423 --> 07:05.884
You were looking
at Katie Yost.

07:05.884 --> 07:07.468
And there's nothing
wrong with that.

07:07.468 --> 07:09.096
In fact, I think
you should ask her out.

07:09.096 --> 07:11.056
Oh, no...
I couldn't do that.

07:11.056 --> 07:13.058
Why not? She's unattached.

07:13.058 --> 07:14.434
What if she said no?

07:14.434 --> 07:16.186
Hmm...

07:16.186 --> 07:19.147
"A faint heart
never won fair maiden."

07:24.194 --> 07:26.571
Maybe later.

07:33.120 --> 07:35.247
I remember
when I was that young.

07:35.247 --> 07:36.957
Yeah, they're green,

07:36.957 --> 07:39.167
but I'll whip 'em
into shape.

07:39.167 --> 07:40.710
Remember, I learned
from the best.

07:40.710 --> 07:42.963
And you've turned
into a fine leader.

07:42.963 --> 07:44.881
Thanks.

07:44.881 --> 07:46.549
I got to admit,

07:46.549 --> 07:49.219
I was surprised to hear
you turned down Collins' offer.

07:49.219 --> 07:50.804
Well, I had my reasons.

07:50.804 --> 07:53.265
She's a very pretty one.

07:53.265 --> 07:54.975
You got a girl
waiting for you back home?

07:54.975 --> 07:56.726
Not me.
I'm surprised.

07:56.726 --> 07:58.478
You always were
lucky with the ladies.

07:58.478 --> 07:59.813
[CHUCKLES]

07:59.813 --> 08:01.273
Ancient history.

08:01.273 --> 08:03.942
"The greatest reward in life

08:03.942 --> 08:06.820
is to serve others with
a single-minded purpose."

08:06.820 --> 08:09.114
Now, why does that
sound so familiar?

08:09.114 --> 08:10.407
It's a quote from--

08:10.407 --> 08:13.576
BOTH:
--Sergeant Major Brookings.

08:14.953 --> 08:17.372
He was the wisest man
in the regiment,

08:17.372 --> 08:19.166
and a real hero.

08:21.376 --> 08:24.296
If I had someone
waiting for me at home,

08:24.296 --> 08:27.299
I just couldn't do
what I'm supposed to do.

08:27.299 --> 08:29.009
I couldn't serve the way
I know I should.

08:29.009 --> 08:31.803
The way I was intended to.
You know what I mean?

08:31.803 --> 08:34.139
I know exactly what you mean.

08:34.139 --> 08:35.723
But you found
your purpose here.

08:35.723 --> 08:37.767
I have.

08:39.394 --> 08:41.062
So...

08:41.062 --> 08:43.606
you got any plans for tonight?

08:43.606 --> 08:45.275
Not really. Why?

08:45.275 --> 08:47.152
How much do you like pot roast?

08:50.571 --> 08:51.865
Mr. Wyatt?

08:51.865 --> 08:53.574
Do you have
a moment?

08:53.574 --> 08:54.993
What's it about?

08:54.993 --> 08:57.120
Um...

08:57.120 --> 08:59.122
It's the school.

08:59.122 --> 09:00.374
It's getting very crowded.

09:00.374 --> 09:02.334
And you're
telling me this because...

09:02.334 --> 09:03.877
Well, it isn't fair
to the children,

09:03.877 --> 09:06.046
and a lot of them
come from railroad families.

09:06.046 --> 09:08.382
Let's see... first,
you have a problem

09:08.382 --> 09:10.091
with the men here
working long hours,

09:10.091 --> 09:12.593
now you have a problem with
the school being too crowded.

09:12.593 --> 09:14.679
You seem to have
a lot of issues, don't you?

09:14.679 --> 09:17.391
[CHUCKLES]
Uh, I just feel

09:17.391 --> 09:19.767
that the railroad isn't paying
its fair share.

09:19.767 --> 09:21.602
You're taking advantage
of Hope Valley.

09:21.602 --> 09:23.980
We're a business,
Miss Thatcher,

09:23.980 --> 09:25.732
and you're a schoolteacher.

09:25.732 --> 09:28.609
And frankly, what we do
is none of your concern.

09:28.609 --> 09:30.028
Mr. Wyatt,

09:30.028 --> 09:31.946
I teach my students fairness.

09:31.946 --> 09:33.656
I teach them
to be good citizens--

09:33.656 --> 09:35.158
I really don't have time
for this.

09:35.158 --> 09:37.202
Well, maybe, I should reach
out to the community

09:37.202 --> 09:38.786
and let them know
what's going on.

09:38.786 --> 09:40.621
Or maybe the newspaper
should print a story

09:40.621 --> 09:42.207
about how overcrowded
the school is,

09:42.207 --> 09:44.459
and how the railroad
isn't pulling its weight.

09:44.459 --> 09:46.586
It sounds like you're
making this into a crusade.

09:46.586 --> 09:49.464
I never give up
on my students.

09:53.760 --> 09:55.011
[DOOR SLAMS]

09:55.011 --> 09:57.264
She's becoming
a problem.

09:57.264 --> 09:59.307
Every problem
has a solution.

10:10.444 --> 10:12.487
Finish your spaghetti,
and we'll play dominos.

10:12.487 --> 10:15.031
It's not the same
without Pastor Frank.

10:15.031 --> 10:17.576
Well, we'll still
have fun, won't we?

10:17.576 --> 10:19.953
I wish you guys
were talking again.

10:19.953 --> 10:24.458
Cody, sometimes grownups
need a little time apart,

10:24.458 --> 10:26.501
especially when they're not
seeing eye to eye.

10:26.501 --> 10:27.919
What does that mean?

10:27.919 --> 10:29.754
You know when you and Robert
play baseball,

10:29.754 --> 10:31.256
and you both
want to be the pitcher,

10:31.256 --> 10:32.715
but neither of you
wants to give in?

10:32.715 --> 10:35.218
Yeah, but then
we figure it out.

10:35.218 --> 10:37.345
Well...

10:37.345 --> 10:39.973
Pastor Frank and I haven't quite
figured it out yet.

10:39.973 --> 10:42.767
But you will, won't you?

10:44.269 --> 10:45.562
Why don't I get you a slice

10:45.562 --> 10:48.189
of that chocolate cake
I promised?

10:52.235 --> 10:55.238
[♪♪♪]

10:55.238 --> 10:57.657
[BRISK DANCE MUSIC PLAYING]

11:09.252 --> 11:11.754
[SONG ENDS]

11:13.756 --> 11:15.216
[LAUGHING]

11:15.216 --> 11:16.926
You are such
a good dancer.

11:16.926 --> 11:18.637
Oh, I'm sure
Jack's better than I am.

11:18.637 --> 11:21.348
Oh, no, no, I yield to you
on this, sir.

11:21.348 --> 11:22.599
Did you take lessons?

11:22.599 --> 11:24.643
No, but my mom loved to dance.

11:24.643 --> 11:28.021
My dad traveled a lot,
so I filled in.

11:28.021 --> 11:29.230
How is your mom?

11:29.230 --> 11:30.524
Good.

11:30.524 --> 11:32.567
She's always asking about you.

11:32.567 --> 11:34.819
She thinks of Jack as a son.

11:34.819 --> 11:36.946
Sometimes, I think
she likes him better than me.

11:36.946 --> 11:38.323
[CHUCKLES]

11:38.323 --> 11:40.116
Well, he is
very lovable.

11:41.451 --> 11:43.662
It's getting late,
I better hit the sack.

11:43.662 --> 11:45.038
Thank you
for the hospitality,

11:45.038 --> 11:46.665
Miss Thatcher.

11:46.665 --> 11:49.000
Oh, we've danced the foxtrot,
you can call me Elizabeth.

11:49.000 --> 11:50.335
Yes, ma'am.

11:51.503 --> 11:53.880
I really admire
what you're doing.

11:53.880 --> 11:55.507
Just be safe.

11:55.507 --> 11:57.008
That's the plan.

12:01.388 --> 12:03.014
Doug.

12:12.815 --> 12:14.775
He seems so young
to be leading all those men.

12:14.775 --> 12:16.194
Do you think he's up to it?

12:16.194 --> 12:18.154
I'll be praying for him.

12:18.154 --> 12:20.407
Then I will, too.

12:24.035 --> 12:25.495
[♪♪♪]

12:29.583 --> 12:31.125
What, no breakfast?

12:31.125 --> 12:32.419
Oh.

12:32.419 --> 12:35.380
I'm sorry, Lee,
I've just been so busy.

12:35.380 --> 12:37.716
Doing what?
My column.

12:37.716 --> 12:39.384
The time I spent
working at the cafe

12:39.384 --> 12:40.885
has put my finger

12:40.885 --> 12:42.929
back on the pulse
of what's going on around here.

12:42.929 --> 12:46.349
It's as if the whole town
desperately needs my advice.

12:46.349 --> 12:48.059
They're
deprived of love!

12:48.059 --> 12:49.644
[MUTTERING]
I'm deprived of food.

12:49.644 --> 12:51.062
Oh, listen to this one.

12:51.062 --> 12:53.356
"When two grownups
are mad at each other,

12:53.356 --> 12:55.900
how do you make them
not mad at each other anymore?"

12:55.900 --> 12:57.360
"Grownups?"

12:57.360 --> 12:59.613
And it's signed "Anonymous,"
spelled incorrectly,

12:59.613 --> 13:02.073
which means it must be
one of Elizabeth's students.

13:02.073 --> 13:03.533
Oh, my goodness!

13:03.533 --> 13:04.992
This is from Cody!

13:04.992 --> 13:07.287
Cody? What makes you think
it's from Cody?

13:07.287 --> 13:09.038
Well, I saw Abigail
and Frank yesterday.

13:09.038 --> 13:11.999
Let's just say,
there is trouble in paradise.

13:11.999 --> 13:14.335
Well then,

13:14.335 --> 13:17.004
I certainly have
my work cut out for me.

13:17.004 --> 13:18.548
Sweetheart, maybe
we should just

13:18.548 --> 13:20.550
stay out of
their business, hmm?

13:20.550 --> 13:23.886
Lee! This is my job!

13:23.886 --> 13:25.680
What kind of advice
columnist would I be

13:25.680 --> 13:27.014
if I didn't
come to the rescue

13:27.014 --> 13:29.850
of a sticky little
tow-headed boy? Oh...

13:29.850 --> 13:31.102
Okay. Yes, dear.

13:31.102 --> 13:33.229
Okay. Okay...

13:38.109 --> 13:39.402
Need a hand?

13:39.402 --> 13:40.987
No, I'm good, thanks.

13:40.987 --> 13:42.863
I haven't seen you
around here before.

13:42.863 --> 13:44.240
Jesse Flynn.

13:44.240 --> 13:45.908
I work up at the sawmill.

13:45.908 --> 13:47.118
Carson Shepherd.

13:47.118 --> 13:48.827
I just started
with the railroad.

13:48.827 --> 13:50.913
Good luck.

13:52.707 --> 13:54.041
MAN:
Look out!

13:54.041 --> 13:55.376
[PEOPLE SHOUTING IN PANIC]

14:00.590 --> 14:01.840
Are you all right?

14:01.840 --> 14:03.802
[GASPS AND SHOUTS
OF CONCERN]

14:06.929 --> 14:08.264
Biddy Betsy almost got hurt.

14:08.264 --> 14:09.808
[WINCING]
Mm-hm.

14:09.808 --> 14:11.058
Are you okay?

14:11.058 --> 14:12.352
Yeah.

14:12.352 --> 14:13.894
I'm fine, just...

14:13.894 --> 14:15.229
run along.

14:18.232 --> 14:19.526
You all right?

14:19.526 --> 14:21.027
Sure.

14:21.027 --> 14:23.780
I'm just gonna sit here
for a while.

14:25.490 --> 14:27.033
[WINCING]

14:29.869 --> 14:32.706
Oh! There he is.
Good morning, young man.

14:32.706 --> 14:34.374
I suppose you're
on your way to school.

14:34.374 --> 14:36.459
Yes.
Well, shall we?

14:36.459 --> 14:38.545
You're going
to school, too?

14:38.545 --> 14:39.838
[CHUCKLES]
No, silly.

14:39.838 --> 14:41.130
But I'm walking you
to school

14:41.130 --> 14:43.090
because you and I have
a lot to talk about.

14:43.090 --> 14:45.719
We do?
I got your letter.

14:45.719 --> 14:47.470
How did you know
it was from me?

14:47.470 --> 14:48.929
[CHUCKLES]
It doesn't matter.

14:48.929 --> 14:50.765
What does matter is,
I think I can help you

14:50.765 --> 14:52.767
with Miss Abigail
and Pastor Frank.

14:52.767 --> 14:54.227
That's great!

14:54.227 --> 14:56.103
I wrote down
this lovely little poem

14:56.103 --> 14:57.438
by Elizabeth Barrett Browning.

14:57.438 --> 14:58.732
A poem?

14:58.732 --> 15:00.358
Well, not just any poem.

15:00.358 --> 15:04.111
One of the most romantic poems
ever written.

15:04.111 --> 15:06.155
How do I love thee?

15:06.155 --> 15:07.741
Let me count the ways.

15:07.741 --> 15:09.325
I love thee
to the depth and breadth

15:09.325 --> 15:10.869
and height my soul--

15:10.869 --> 15:12.412
I'm gonna be late
for school--

15:12.412 --> 15:14.914
Of course you are.
All you need to do

15:14.914 --> 15:17.208
is slip this
into Pastor Frank's jacket.

15:17.208 --> 15:18.459
When he finds it,

15:18.459 --> 15:20.253
he will know that
it's from Miss Abigail,

15:20.253 --> 15:22.756
and it will absolutely
melt his heart.

15:22.756 --> 15:24.048
Guaranteed.

15:24.048 --> 15:25.508
That's a great idea!

15:25.508 --> 15:28.135
[LAUGHS]
Those are the only kind I have.

15:36.977 --> 15:38.772
Philip...

15:38.772 --> 15:40.106
would you like
some help?

15:40.106 --> 15:41.441
I'm done.

15:41.441 --> 15:43.150
Are you sure?

15:43.150 --> 15:45.152
I don't see anything there
about your mother.

15:45.152 --> 15:46.863
She died.

15:48.989 --> 15:50.366
My dad died, too,

15:50.366 --> 15:52.034
but I still wrote
lots of things down.

15:53.202 --> 15:55.496
See? He taught me how to fish,

15:55.496 --> 15:57.749
and all the words
to Saint Francis' prayer.

15:57.749 --> 15:59.584
That's wonderful, Harper.

16:01.085 --> 16:03.504
I don't want
to do this anymore.

16:04.798 --> 16:06.674
Okay, uh...

16:06.674 --> 16:08.718
time for recess, everyone.

16:15.224 --> 16:16.935
Maybe...

16:16.935 --> 16:19.479
you could tell me one thing
you remember about your mommy,

16:19.479 --> 16:21.105
and I could help you
write it down.

16:21.105 --> 16:22.982
But I don't know anything.

16:22.982 --> 16:25.401
Well, I'm sure your daddy's
told you something about her.

16:25.401 --> 16:27.236
I'm not allowed
to talk about her.

16:27.236 --> 16:29.029
Why not?

16:31.866 --> 16:34.577
Because I took her away.

16:34.577 --> 16:36.704
You took her away?
I don't under--

16:39.916 --> 16:42.001
Oh.

16:42.001 --> 16:43.544
She died when you were born.

16:43.544 --> 16:45.922
It's my fault
that she's not here.

16:45.922 --> 16:47.173
No, that's not true, Philip.

16:47.173 --> 16:48.633
Yes, it is,

16:48.633 --> 16:50.593
and that's why
my daddy doesn't love me.

16:50.593 --> 16:52.386
No.

16:52.386 --> 16:54.848
No matter what you think,

16:54.848 --> 16:56.891
it is not your fault.

16:58.476 --> 17:00.478
I want to go to recess now.

17:06.400 --> 17:07.986
Thank you.

17:07.986 --> 17:09.445
Mr. Gowen?

17:09.445 --> 17:11.238
This letter
just came in for you.

17:11.238 --> 17:12.657
Special Delivery.

17:12.657 --> 17:13.950
Oh, thank you so much.

17:27.922 --> 17:29.716
Well, that's grand.

17:32.969 --> 17:35.262
There you go.

17:35.262 --> 17:37.765
Try to keep it dry.

17:38.558 --> 17:39.893
Mr. Shepherd,

17:39.893 --> 17:41.769
please...

17:42.812 --> 17:45.565
How did you get hurt?

17:45.565 --> 17:47.608
Ah, just...
just clumsy.

17:47.608 --> 17:49.736
Let's see.

17:56.075 --> 17:57.744
You might have pulled
a costal muscle.

17:57.744 --> 17:59.412
It's more likely
a hairline fract--

17:59.412 --> 18:00.955
Uh...

18:00.955 --> 18:03.583
I think I cracked a rib.

18:03.583 --> 18:07.045
All I need
is a compression wrap.

18:07.045 --> 18:09.589
You know a lot
about these things, don't you?

18:09.589 --> 18:10.757
I work for the railroad.

18:10.757 --> 18:13.092
I've been injured
more than once.

18:13.092 --> 18:15.177
Well, it'll be
the last time for a while.

18:15.177 --> 18:17.805
Whether it's a fracture
or a torn muscle,

18:17.805 --> 18:19.891
you won't be able
to perform strenuous labor

18:19.891 --> 18:21.434
for some time.

18:21.434 --> 18:23.978
You see, the railroad's
got a funny rule about that.

18:23.978 --> 18:27.189
If you don't work,
you don't get paid.

18:27.189 --> 18:29.817
And I'm kind of fond of eating.

18:29.817 --> 18:31.652
Just wrap me up,

18:31.652 --> 18:33.404
I'll be fine.

18:33.404 --> 18:35.949
If you do more damage to your
ribs, it might become permanent.

18:35.949 --> 18:37.491
You should think
about the long term.

18:37.491 --> 18:39.535
My stomach only cares
about today.

18:46.834 --> 18:48.878
I'm not sure when
I'll see you again,

18:48.878 --> 18:50.421
so take care of yourself.

18:50.421 --> 18:52.882
You fight
the good fight, Doug.

19:01.557 --> 19:03.225
Good luck, boys.

19:12.276 --> 19:14.695
Mounties! Move out!

19:42.640 --> 19:43.975
Mr. Cantrell...

19:45.768 --> 19:47.103
Is Philip all right?

19:47.103 --> 19:48.938
He's fine, I just need to talk
to you.

19:48.938 --> 19:50.148
I'm on the clock.

19:50.148 --> 19:52.025
Please?
It's important.

19:54.485 --> 19:55.987
What's going on?

19:55.987 --> 19:59.157
Um, your son said something
that has me concerned.

19:59.157 --> 20:00.449
It's about his mother.

20:00.449 --> 20:02.160
Philip said

20:02.160 --> 20:04.078
he's the reason
she's not here anymore.

20:04.078 --> 20:05.245
Excuse me?

20:05.245 --> 20:06.914
He thinks
it's his fault she died,

20:06.914 --> 20:09.291
and that you blame him for that.
Well, I never said that.

20:09.291 --> 20:11.669
Whether you said it or not,
he thinks you feel that way.

20:11.669 --> 20:13.004
That's ridiculous.

20:13.004 --> 20:14.463
Of course it is.

20:14.463 --> 20:16.799
And if you could just
sit down and talk to him,

20:16.799 --> 20:18.467
and explain
what happened.

20:18.467 --> 20:20.720
I knew going to school was
going to be too much for him.

20:20.720 --> 20:22.262
He's too young.
No, that's not

20:22.262 --> 20:23.848
what this is about.
I'm afraid it is.

20:23.848 --> 20:26.559
Well, taking him out of school
isn't the answer.

20:26.559 --> 20:27.894
It is for me.

20:27.894 --> 20:29.687
I gotta get back to work.

20:29.687 --> 20:31.647
Mr. Cantrell...

20:32.982 --> 20:35.526
[SIGHS]

20:37.111 --> 20:39.572
I don't know,
I still say we just move on.

20:39.572 --> 20:41.323
But don't you see?

20:41.323 --> 20:43.534
Everybody thinks
we're already gone.

20:43.534 --> 20:45.452
That payroll will be
easy pickins'.

20:46.620 --> 20:47.914
You got a plan?

20:47.914 --> 20:50.666
I always got a plan.

20:53.419 --> 20:55.295
Henry...

20:56.630 --> 20:58.091
What are you doing
behind my desk?

20:58.091 --> 21:00.593
Well, some good news.

21:00.593 --> 21:04.055
You needn't consider it
your desk any longer.

21:04.055 --> 21:06.140
What are you talking about?

21:06.140 --> 21:08.517
Well, they suspended
the investigation against me,

21:08.517 --> 21:09.977
dropped all the charges.

21:11.478 --> 21:13.981
And now your services
as mayor of Hope Valley

21:13.981 --> 21:15.733
will no longer be needed.

21:27.661 --> 21:29.872
I went to the campsite,
looking for you.

21:34.710 --> 21:37.171
We need to finish
our conversation.

21:37.171 --> 21:39.298
Look, I appreciate
that you care about Philip,

21:39.298 --> 21:40.841
but I know what's best for him.

21:40.841 --> 21:42.135
But you can't let him believe

21:42.135 --> 21:43.677
that he's the reason
his mother died.

21:43.677 --> 21:45.304
And you can't keep
shutting him out.

21:45.304 --> 21:47.098
I don't shut him out.
Yes, you do.

21:49.100 --> 21:51.185
Do you know
that Philip's favorite book

21:51.185 --> 21:52.686
is "Quack Quack Duck"?

21:52.686 --> 21:54.105
Or that he drinks
all his milk

21:54.105 --> 21:55.856
before starting
his sandwich at lunch?

21:55.856 --> 21:57.483
Or that he can't even
say "sandwich,"

21:57.483 --> 21:59.277
so he calls it his "sang-wich?"

21:59.277 --> 22:01.862
Your little boy
needs you, Mr. Cantrell.

22:01.862 --> 22:04.323
He needs you to give him a hug
every now and again.

22:04.323 --> 22:07.785
He needs you to love him
as much as he loves you.

22:07.785 --> 22:09.870
Of course, I love him.

22:09.870 --> 22:13.207
But you're holding back.

22:14.959 --> 22:17.211
My wife...

22:17.211 --> 22:20.380
she wasn't supposed to die.

22:20.380 --> 22:22.424
We were supposed to be
a family together.

22:22.424 --> 22:23.717
I know.

22:25.385 --> 22:28.639
But it wasn't Philip's fault
that his mother died.

22:28.639 --> 22:30.975
It wasn't fair, either.

22:30.975 --> 22:32.476
Life isn't fair.

22:32.476 --> 22:34.561
We have to go on.

22:35.771 --> 22:37.648
And there's
a little boy out there

22:37.648 --> 22:42.028
who is in desperate need
of a real father.

22:42.028 --> 22:43.779
One who will laugh with him,

22:43.779 --> 22:45.323
and read to him,

22:45.323 --> 22:47.867
and dry his tears.

22:49.660 --> 22:51.578
Please...

22:51.578 --> 22:53.956
forgive him,

22:53.956 --> 22:56.125
and let go of what happened.

22:59.086 --> 23:01.714
Good night, Miss Thatcher.

23:14.977 --> 23:16.436
[♪♪♪]

23:22.360 --> 23:23.694
That's about it!

23:29.825 --> 23:31.327
Thanks for
your help, Murph.

23:31.327 --> 23:33.453
My pleasure. Looked like
you had your hands full.

23:33.453 --> 23:35.455
I appreciate it.
I'd better get back to work.

23:35.455 --> 23:36.707
Okay.

23:36.707 --> 23:38.042
Take care, Pastor.

23:49.511 --> 23:50.846
[SIGHS]

23:58.145 --> 24:00.647
I don't understand, what
happened with the investigation

24:00.647 --> 24:02.482
against Mr. Gowen?
It was dropped.

24:02.482 --> 24:03.984
But Jack said

24:03.984 --> 24:06.362
the Inspector General had
solid evidence against him.

24:06.362 --> 24:07.947
They did. But the accountant

24:07.947 --> 24:10.532
who was going to testify
against him changed his story,

24:10.532 --> 24:12.368
swears it was
a bookkeeping mistake.

24:12.368 --> 24:13.953
Isn't that convenient?

24:13.953 --> 24:15.746
Somehow Mr. Gowen
always finds a way out.

24:15.746 --> 24:17.748
Not this time.
Well, I thought you said

24:17.748 --> 24:19.083
the Mounties
dropped the case.

24:19.083 --> 24:20.834
They did, but
I'm not a Mountie.

24:20.834 --> 24:23.421
This smells like a payoff,
pure and simple to me.

24:23.421 --> 24:25.463
Now all I have
to do is prove it.

24:25.463 --> 24:27.300
Ladies...

24:27.300 --> 24:28.884
After all you've done
for the town,

24:28.884 --> 24:31.095
he thinks he can just waltz in
like nothing happened.

24:31.095 --> 24:32.346
Well, at least

24:32.346 --> 24:33.973
I'll get to spend
more time with Cody.

24:33.973 --> 24:35.891
That's true.
You sure you're okay?

24:35.891 --> 24:37.268
You seem calm.

24:37.268 --> 24:38.518
I am calm.

24:38.518 --> 24:40.354
At least for now.

24:43.607 --> 24:45.692
Mr. Coulter.
Mrs. Coulter.

24:45.692 --> 24:46.944
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa...

24:46.944 --> 24:49.613
What are you
so happy about?

24:49.613 --> 24:50.864
You won't believe it,

24:50.864 --> 24:52.783
but I found this
in my jacket.

24:52.783 --> 24:55.161
I think it might be
from Miss Yost.

24:56.996 --> 24:58.496
Okay, what does it say?

24:58.496 --> 24:59.873
How do I love thee?

24:59.873 --> 25:03.877
Let me count the ways...

25:03.877 --> 25:05.171
Oh...

25:06.588 --> 25:07.881
How sweet.

25:07.881 --> 25:09.383
[GIGGLES AWKWARDLY]

25:09.383 --> 25:11.718
[QUIETLY]
Doesn't he have
something he needs to do?

25:11.718 --> 25:13.553
Huh?

25:13.553 --> 25:17.224
Uh, yes, right.
Inventory reports, uh,

25:17.224 --> 25:18.558
need to be taken
to the mill.

25:18.558 --> 25:19.852
They're on my desk.

25:19.852 --> 25:21.561
Yes, sir. Yup.

25:23.897 --> 25:25.232
Okay.

25:25.232 --> 25:26.650
What was all that about?

25:26.650 --> 25:28.110
That poem!

25:28.110 --> 25:29.527
I gave it to Cody
to give to Frank.

25:29.527 --> 25:31.155
It was supposed to be
from Abigail.

25:31.155 --> 25:32.572
Excuse me?

25:32.572 --> 25:34.532
Oh, you can never depend
on a little boy

25:34.532 --> 25:36.743
to do anything right.
Now poor Murphy,

25:36.743 --> 25:38.245
he thinks he has
a secret admirer,

25:38.245 --> 25:40.456
and I cannot break his heart.

25:40.456 --> 25:42.124
What am I going to do?

25:42.124 --> 25:44.168
Fix it.

25:44.168 --> 25:45.919
That's what
you're gonna do.

25:45.919 --> 25:47.296
Come...

25:47.296 --> 25:48.630
[FRETTING]
Oh...

25:50.548 --> 25:53.219
And don't forget
to work on your family trees.

25:57.097 --> 25:59.183
What can I do for you,
Mr. Wyatt?

25:59.183 --> 26:01.352
I've been thinking about
the conversation we had.

26:01.352 --> 26:02.728
And?

26:02.728 --> 26:04.813
I don't often say this, but...

26:04.813 --> 26:07.274
you were right, and I was wrong.

26:07.274 --> 26:08.692
The railroad
is the main reason

26:08.692 --> 26:10.027
for all
your new students,

26:10.027 --> 26:11.611
and we need
to do our part.

26:11.611 --> 26:13.155
What does that mean, exactly?

26:13.155 --> 26:14.740
National Pacific
is going to give you

26:14.740 --> 26:16.783
twice the current budget
of the school.

26:16.783 --> 26:20.954
You won't be short on supplies,
or books, or anything else.

26:20.954 --> 26:23.332
Mr. Wyatt, I can't tell you
how much I appreciate that,

26:23.332 --> 26:24.958
and-and, in fact,

26:24.958 --> 26:27.336
the whole town will be thrilled
when they hear about it.

26:27.336 --> 26:29.171
Consider it an investment
in the students,

26:29.171 --> 26:31.673
and the future of Hope Valley.

26:45.438 --> 26:47.147
I really messed up, didn't I?

26:47.147 --> 26:49.858
Cody, it's all right.

26:49.858 --> 26:52.694
You're just a little boy
who makes mistakes now and then.

26:52.694 --> 26:54.071
Mostly now.

26:54.071 --> 26:57.074
But the good news is,
I have another idea.

26:58.867 --> 27:00.494
Chocolates?
Mm-hm--

27:00.494 --> 27:04.164
Cody! Cody, it's time for you
to do your homework.

27:04.164 --> 27:07.167
But you said
I could play with Robert.

27:07.167 --> 27:09.669
Okay, but I want you
back inside in an hour.

27:15.926 --> 27:17.261
Hmm.

27:20.598 --> 27:22.099
As I was saying,

27:22.099 --> 27:23.350
all you need to do

27:23.350 --> 27:25.478
is leave these
at Pastor Frank's door.

27:25.478 --> 27:26.686
When he finds them,

27:26.686 --> 27:28.481
he'll think they're from
Miss Abigail.

27:28.481 --> 27:29.731
He'll come here,

27:29.731 --> 27:31.484
they'll run
into each other's arms...

27:31.484 --> 27:33.735
[GASPING IN DELIGHT]
and all will be wonderful.

27:33.735 --> 27:35.613
Thanks for the help,
Miss Rosemary.

27:35.613 --> 27:37.239
[GIGGLES]
It's what I do.

27:47.166 --> 27:49.001
[CLEARING THROAT]
Abigail...

27:49.001 --> 27:51.795
I've been meaning
to talk to you.

27:51.795 --> 27:53.839
You've heard Dottie's
opening a dress shop?

27:53.839 --> 27:55.048
I have.

27:55.048 --> 27:57.426
Well, you know I love to sew...

27:58.885 --> 28:01.054
I guess what I'm trying
to say is...

28:01.054 --> 28:03.182
well, now that
you're not mayor anymore,

28:03.182 --> 28:04.850
and you have more time
for the cafe...

28:04.850 --> 28:07.311
You would like to work there.
I didn't want to talk to her

28:07.311 --> 28:09.522
until I knew
it was okay with you.

28:09.522 --> 28:11.231
Clara, you've been a godsend,

28:11.231 --> 28:12.650
but if it's time for you

28:12.650 --> 28:14.234
to start a new chapter
in your life.

28:14.234 --> 28:15.569
Of course, you have my blessing.

28:15.569 --> 28:18.322
You sure you don't mind?

28:18.322 --> 28:20.366
I was going to take
that "help wanted" sign down,

28:20.366 --> 28:22.993
but it looks like it's staying
in the window permanently.

28:22.993 --> 28:24.953
[CHUCKLING TOGETHER]

28:26.872 --> 28:30.750
Oh, look at Murphy,
chatting up Katie Yost.

28:30.750 --> 28:33.003
You should have more faith
in your wife's skills

28:33.003 --> 28:34.796
as a matchmaker.

28:34.796 --> 28:37.799
It's not your skill,
it's Cody's mistake.

28:37.799 --> 28:39.426
Love doesn't
make mistakes.

28:39.426 --> 28:40.969
It's only a matter of time

28:40.969 --> 28:44.806
before those two lovebirds
are waltzing down the aisle.

28:44.806 --> 28:46.475
I wouldn't
save the date just yet.

28:46.475 --> 28:49.269
Oh, don't be
such a sourpuss.

28:49.269 --> 28:51.730
[CHUCKLING FONDLY]

28:51.730 --> 28:54.650
JACK:
The railroad is doubling
the budget for the school?

28:54.650 --> 28:56.068
ELIZABETH:
Mm-hm.

28:56.068 --> 28:58.070
That's more than
you could have dreamed of.

28:58.070 --> 28:59.405
[SIGHS]

28:59.405 --> 29:01.823
You are one
persuasive lady.

29:01.823 --> 29:03.783
Not always.

29:03.783 --> 29:06.370
Give Philip's dad some time,
I'm sure he'll come around.

29:06.370 --> 29:09.373
I just hope I haven't
pushed him too far.

29:09.373 --> 29:11.584
You told him the truth
about his son.

29:11.584 --> 29:13.377
He needed to hear it.

29:14.836 --> 29:16.255
[SIGHS HEAVILY]

29:17.756 --> 29:19.216
I'm glad I found you.

29:19.216 --> 29:21.677
You dropped this
at the infirmary.

29:25.389 --> 29:26.724
Thank you.

29:27.933 --> 29:30.227
That's a lovely photo.

29:30.227 --> 29:31.645
Who is it?

29:35.274 --> 29:36.692
Enjoy your evening.

30:00.257 --> 30:01.550
Jack!

30:06.012 --> 30:07.556
The Tates
are robbing the bank.

30:07.556 --> 30:08.848
They've got Jenkins.

30:10.142 --> 30:12.478
Bill and Wyatt are in there
counting payroll.

30:15.648 --> 30:17.816
I need a diversion
so I can get close. Go.

30:17.816 --> 30:19.151
You got it.

30:25.449 --> 30:28.327
Elizabeth, I need you
to stay here,

30:28.327 --> 30:29.662
but don't let
anyone leave.

30:29.662 --> 30:31.371
I won't.
Just be careful.

30:36.669 --> 30:39.045
Didn't know
there'd be a crowd.

30:39.045 --> 30:41.340
Lose the gun.

30:49.348 --> 30:51.517
Let Jenkins go,
you don't need him.

30:51.517 --> 30:53.226
Put everything
back in the bags,

30:53.226 --> 30:54.978
and hurry up!

30:55.937 --> 30:57.523
You know he's going
to kill us.

30:57.523 --> 30:58.940
Not if I can help it.

30:59.983 --> 31:01.485
Fill the bags.

31:06.657 --> 31:07.991
[COCKS GUN]

31:07.991 --> 31:09.576
Glenn Tate, is that you?

31:09.576 --> 31:11.244
Matt Landry...

31:11.244 --> 31:12.663
what are you doing here?

31:12.663 --> 31:13.997
Ruining your plans.

31:13.997 --> 31:15.290
[GUNSHOT ECHOES]

31:20.337 --> 31:22.172
I wouldn't.

31:23.340 --> 31:24.633
Drop it!

31:31.890 --> 31:33.559
[♪♪♪]

31:39.022 --> 31:40.607
Thanks for what
you did last night.

31:40.607 --> 31:42.025
Ah, it was
no big deal.

31:42.025 --> 31:44.027
Yes, it was.

31:44.027 --> 31:45.445
I know we've had
our differences,

31:45.445 --> 31:48.782
but I think
I misjudged you.

31:48.782 --> 31:51.827
Well, you can make it up
by buying me a drink.

31:51.827 --> 31:53.995
Sounds good.

31:55.455 --> 31:57.624
Jack said they couldn't have
caught the robbers

31:57.624 --> 31:58.958
without Frank.

31:58.958 --> 32:01.044
Well, I'm glad
everyone's safe.

32:01.044 --> 32:03.296
You two still
aren't talking?

32:03.296 --> 32:05.131
I guess we're both being
a little stubborn.

32:05.131 --> 32:06.508
[CHUCKLING]
A little?

32:06.508 --> 32:08.468
Did you hear, Abigail?
About?

32:08.468 --> 32:12.055
Mayor Gowen just waived
all taxes for the railroad.

32:12.055 --> 32:14.224
They won't pay
a single dime to Hope Valley.

32:14.224 --> 32:16.059
I knew it would have
been better for the town

32:16.059 --> 32:18.186
if you had stayed on
as our mayor.

32:20.021 --> 32:21.231
Can you believe it?

32:21.231 --> 32:22.775
The minute he gets
his office back,

32:22.775 --> 32:25.151
he gives them
everything they want.

32:27.613 --> 32:29.239
Where are you going?

32:43.086 --> 32:46.673
Well, isn't this cozy?

32:46.673 --> 32:48.634
Good morning, Abigail,
we're just in a meeting.

32:48.634 --> 32:50.302
I'm sure
congratulating each other.

32:50.302 --> 32:51.804
You suddenly become mayor,

32:51.804 --> 32:53.806
and you suddenly getting
everything you want.

32:53.806 --> 32:55.849
I don't like what
you're implying, Mrs. Stanton.

32:55.849 --> 32:57.893
And I don't like that
you two worked out a deal.

32:57.893 --> 32:59.519
You disappointed me, Henry.

32:59.519 --> 33:01.396
I gave you
a second chance.

33:01.396 --> 33:03.732
I really wanted to believe
that you'd changed.

33:03.732 --> 33:05.734
Perhaps you weren't cut out
for being mayor.

33:05.734 --> 33:07.569
If being mayor
means cheating this town,

33:07.569 --> 33:08.946
then you're right.

33:08.946 --> 33:10.280
Careful, Abigail.

33:10.280 --> 33:12.115
No, Henry,

33:12.115 --> 33:13.951
you be careful.

33:23.543 --> 33:24.962
Cody!

33:28.173 --> 33:29.633
How did our little plan go?

33:29.633 --> 33:30.884
It didn't.

33:30.884 --> 33:33.470
Oh, no!
What happened this time?

33:33.470 --> 33:35.848
Well, Robert and I stopped
to play catch.

33:35.848 --> 33:38.057
And?
The chocolates?

33:38.057 --> 33:40.393
And...I put the chocolates
down on the field.

33:40.393 --> 33:41.812
And?

33:41.812 --> 33:44.314
And...I forgot them.

33:44.314 --> 33:46.984
Well then, you go back,
and you get them.

33:46.984 --> 33:48.986
I tried, but they were gone.

33:48.986 --> 33:50.278
[SIGHS IN FRUSTRATION]

33:50.278 --> 33:52.030
Robert!

33:52.030 --> 33:53.448
Did you see
a box of chocolates

33:53.448 --> 33:54.992
on the baseball field?

33:54.992 --> 33:56.326
Oh, I sure did!

33:56.326 --> 33:58.203
They were really good!

34:00.079 --> 34:01.748
Now what?

34:01.748 --> 34:03.834
Well, you know what they say.

34:03.834 --> 34:05.210
If at first
you don't succeed,

34:05.210 --> 34:06.461
try, try again.

34:06.461 --> 34:08.839
We've already tried
and tried again.

34:10.841 --> 34:12.759
I suppose you're right
about that.

34:12.759 --> 34:14.093
You know what else
they say?

34:14.093 --> 34:15.679
What?

34:15.679 --> 34:17.222
Two heads are better than one.

34:17.222 --> 34:18.807
What does that mean?

34:18.807 --> 34:22.978
It means maybe you and I can
come up with an idea together.

34:22.978 --> 34:24.604
Come on...

34:24.604 --> 34:25.856
There you go.

34:25.856 --> 34:27.357
Thank you very much,
Nurse Carter.

34:27.357 --> 34:30.861
[CHUCKLES]
You're very welcome,
Mr. Hikcomb.

34:30.861 --> 34:33.363
Ah, Mr. Shepherd.

34:33.363 --> 34:36.199
How can I help you?

34:36.199 --> 34:38.159
I need something
to kill the pain.

34:38.159 --> 34:39.828
I wouldn't advise that.

34:39.828 --> 34:41.287
I don't want you
to hurt yourself

34:41.287 --> 34:42.748
any worse than you already have.

34:42.748 --> 34:44.249
Then I'll lose my job.

34:44.249 --> 34:47.085
There are other jobs
in Hope Valley.

34:47.085 --> 34:48.336
Nobody knows me here.

34:48.336 --> 34:49.880
Nobody's going to hire me.

34:49.880 --> 34:54.259
I do, and I know of a position
that needs to be filled.

34:54.259 --> 34:56.053
Doing what?

34:59.097 --> 35:00.807
Miss Thatcher!

35:00.807 --> 35:03.643
Philip! Oh, I'm
so happy to see you.

35:03.643 --> 35:05.144
Can I go work
on my family tree?

35:05.144 --> 35:06.396
I want to finish it!

35:06.396 --> 35:09.441
Well, it's right
where you left it.

35:12.027 --> 35:13.445
[SIGHS HAPPILY]

35:13.445 --> 35:15.405
I'm so glad
you changed your mind.

35:15.405 --> 35:17.616
He really belongs
in school.

35:17.616 --> 35:19.367
I thought about what you said,

35:19.367 --> 35:21.327
and it's true.

35:21.327 --> 35:23.747
I was angry about what happened.

35:23.747 --> 35:25.958
I let it get the best of me,

35:25.958 --> 35:28.877
and I shouldn't have
taken it out on him.

35:30.045 --> 35:31.546
Well, that's in the past now.

35:32.505 --> 35:34.967
I made a lot of mistakes.

35:34.967 --> 35:37.677
But that's gonna change now.

35:37.677 --> 35:40.097
I want to do right by my boy.

35:40.097 --> 35:41.347
I want to be a good dad.

35:41.347 --> 35:43.725
I just hope I know how.

35:43.725 --> 35:48.187
Well, you could start
by giving him a hug.

35:54.319 --> 35:56.947
[♪♪♪]

36:17.550 --> 36:19.011
[♪♪♪]

36:23.222 --> 36:26.476
Excuse me, um...
Do you still need help?

36:26.476 --> 36:27.727
If you can cook.

36:27.727 --> 36:29.270
I worked six months
in a chuck wagon

36:29.270 --> 36:30.522
for a crew of miners

36:30.522 --> 36:32.107
before I got a job
with the railroad.

36:32.107 --> 36:33.900
Then you have
experience.

36:33.900 --> 36:36.111
What about references?

36:36.111 --> 36:37.654
The nurse
down at the infirmary,

36:37.654 --> 36:39.322
she's the one that sent me here.

36:39.322 --> 36:41.158
Well, if Faith thinks
he can be trusted...

36:41.158 --> 36:42.450
[DOOR OPENS]

36:42.450 --> 36:43.910
Look! I got an "A"
on my family tree!

36:43.910 --> 36:45.829
Oh, Cody, that's wonderful.
But I'm right

36:45.829 --> 36:47.914
in the middle of a meeting
with this gentleman.

36:47.914 --> 36:50.416
Can we go fishing?
To celebrate?

36:50.416 --> 36:51.877
Oh, sweetheart,
I would love to,

36:51.877 --> 36:53.628
but someone has to work
in the kitchen.

36:53.628 --> 36:55.296
I could start
right now,

36:55.296 --> 36:58.091
if you give me the job.
I could really use it.

36:58.091 --> 37:00.343
And I'm a hard worker.

37:00.343 --> 37:02.054
I don't even know your name.

37:02.054 --> 37:04.056
It's Carson Shepherd.

37:04.056 --> 37:05.807
Please, Miss Abigail?

37:07.308 --> 37:09.644
I'll be around to help
if he needs anything.

37:14.191 --> 37:16.902
Welcome to Abigail's Cafe,
Mr. Shepherd.

37:25.160 --> 37:26.745
What was that
all about?

37:26.745 --> 37:27.996
Never you mind--

37:27.996 --> 37:29.706
[GASPS]
Murphy!

37:29.706 --> 37:32.000
Did you invite
Katie Yost out yet?

37:32.000 --> 37:33.835
Oh, I haven't had the chance.

37:33.835 --> 37:36.295
But I saw the two of you having
a wonderful time together.

37:36.295 --> 37:38.256
But I didn't want
to push my luck.

37:38.256 --> 37:40.550
[GASPS]
Katie! Yoo-hoo!

37:40.550 --> 37:41.927
Yes, Mrs. Coulter?

37:41.927 --> 37:44.221
Could you please
join us for a moment?

37:44.221 --> 37:46.056
Murphy has something
to say to you.

37:46.056 --> 37:47.515
I do?
He does?

37:47.515 --> 37:49.475
Yes. He does.

37:52.771 --> 37:55.232
Fairest Katie...

37:55.232 --> 37:57.358
I deeply apologize

37:57.358 --> 38:00.737
for being an utter goose.

38:00.737 --> 38:02.948
I find myself
thinking of you often...

38:04.449 --> 38:08.411
May I take you
on a picnic tomorrow?

38:09.746 --> 38:11.664
I thought you'd never ask.

38:11.664 --> 38:13.166
I'm free at 1:00.

38:13.166 --> 38:14.375
Oh...

38:14.375 --> 38:16.544
I usually
go for lunch at noon.

38:16.544 --> 38:19.338
I'm sure Mr. Coulter
will make an exception.

38:19.338 --> 38:20.632
1:00 would be fine with me.

38:27.472 --> 38:31.143
Oh, wow,
it's kinda crowded.

38:31.143 --> 38:33.478
Guess I'll go try
somewhere more quiet.

38:46.574 --> 38:48.034
Don't tell me.

38:48.034 --> 38:50.245
Cody invited you.

38:51.496 --> 38:53.206
The fish are biting.

38:53.206 --> 38:56.709
You might as well try
to catch some dinner.

39:09.181 --> 39:11.224
[SIMULTANEOUSLY]
I'm sorry, I--

39:11.224 --> 39:12.642
[CHUCKLING]

39:14.060 --> 39:15.312
Me first.

39:15.312 --> 39:16.771
Please.

39:16.771 --> 39:19.983
It's been so long
since I've had to tell anyone

39:19.983 --> 39:23.528
what I'm doing,
or where I've been,

39:23.528 --> 39:26.281
I guess it kind of
threw me for a loop.

39:28.033 --> 39:31.286
I'm not used to having
anyone worry about me.

39:32.537 --> 39:33.997
Is that a bad thing?

39:33.997 --> 39:35.581
Absolutely not.

39:38.376 --> 39:40.378
I have to admit,

39:40.378 --> 39:42.588
I was scared.

39:42.588 --> 39:44.174
Abigail, you don't
have to worry.

39:44.174 --> 39:46.009
I'm not going to go back
to my outlaw life.

39:46.009 --> 39:47.593
No...

39:47.593 --> 39:50.471
I was scared because I realized
how much I care about you.

39:55.727 --> 39:58.188
Well, it sounds like
we're on the same page.

40:00.481 --> 40:03.276
It sounds like we are.

40:17.916 --> 40:19.334
Everything
all right?

40:21.253 --> 40:23.504
Yeah.

40:23.504 --> 40:26.174
I'm just thinking
about Doug and his men.

40:26.174 --> 40:29.635
They're probably
in the thick of it by now.

40:29.635 --> 40:31.512
Well, if they're
as good at their jobs

40:31.512 --> 40:32.847
as you are at yours,

40:32.847 --> 40:34.807
then they'll be fine.

40:37.977 --> 40:40.605
You just bought yourself
dinner at the saloon.

40:41.814 --> 40:43.358
Why don't you get us a table?

40:43.358 --> 40:44.734
I left my shawl at school.

40:44.734 --> 40:45.985
I'll see you there.

40:45.985 --> 40:47.362
Mm-hm.

40:47.362 --> 40:48.696
Mm-hm.

41:01.418 --> 41:03.711
[CHALK SCRATCHING ON BLACKBOARD]

41:03.711 --> 41:05.297
Excuse me?

41:06.798 --> 41:08.133
Yes?

41:08.133 --> 41:11.552
Uh, why are you writing
on my chalkboard?

41:11.552 --> 41:14.389
Uh, I'm preparing
for tomorrow's lesson.

41:14.389 --> 41:16.057
I don't understand.

41:16.057 --> 41:19.102
Oh, I suppose nobody told you.

41:19.102 --> 41:21.396
I'm your replacement.

41:26.985 --> 41:28.445
[♪♪♪]
